<TITLE> ACC mulls decision to go before JS body </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 8 (bdnews24.com) - The Anticorruption Commission said Wednesday it would decide on a government order to appear before a parliamentary standing committee after examining the legality of the summons. "We will examine the legal aspects of whether an autonomous body is bound to turn up at a parliamentary standing committee meeting," acting chairman of the ACC, Habibur Rahman told bdnews24.com "After that we'll decide whether to attend," Rahman said. The government sent a letter to the commission earlier in the week to attend an Apr 12 meeting of the parliamentary watchdog on government institutions, with all procedural documents of the ACC since its inception, along with its latest annual and audit reports. The letter, which the ACC says it received on Tuesday, said the meeting would discuss the problems of the anti-graft body in discharging its duties. The government appointed Habibur Rahman acting chairman on Tuesday after former chairman Hasan Mashhud Chowdhury quit his office on Apr 2. bdn
